2
00:01:50,792 --> 00:01:55,464
Shakespeare said,
"Life was full of sound and fury,

3
00:01:55,464 --> 00:01:57,883
"and in the end, signified nothing."

4
00:02:00,302 --> 00:02:02,763
Okay, let's begin with Helena.

5
00:02:07,851 --> 00:02:09,895
-Cristal Delgiorno?
-Come in, my darling.

6
00:02:10,103 --> 00:02:11,730
I'm Helena Shepridge.

7
00:02:11,813 --> 00:02:13,899
-Ain't you beautiful?
-Thank you.

8
00:02:13,941 --> 00:02:15,901
Gabriella told me you wanted a reading.

9
00:02:16,235 --> 00:02:18,570
She said you know the future.

10
00:02:19,154 --> 00:02:22,074
I adore Gabriella.
She's such a gifted masseuse.

11
00:02:22,241 --> 00:02:24,785
I must say, I've become addicted
to those massages.

12
00:02:24,826 --> 00:02:27,829
They're the only thing that
relieves the throbbing in my neck.

13
00:02:27,955 --> 00:02:30,624
Will it be cash or check, darling?
Gabriella told you the fee?

14
00:02:30,749 --> 00:02:34,419
Believe me, it's far less expensive.
These fancy psychiatrists I've been seeing...

15
00:02:34,586 --> 00:02:36,797
-Have a little seat, then. Make yourself comfy.
-Thank you.

16
00:02:36,880 --> 00:02:40,092
They sit there all stony-faced
when you need help.

17
00:02:40,092 --> 00:02:44,096
These horrible, horrible medications,
they make me feel even more fidgety.

18
00:02:45,848 --> 00:02:48,141
Is there something I could sip on?

19
00:02:49,184 --> 00:02:50,602
Do you want a cup of tea?

20
00:02:51,186 --> 00:02:52,896
Have you any sherry?

21
00:02:52,938 --> 00:02:55,357
A little drinky. Scotch?

22
00:02:55,399 --> 00:02:57,192
Even better.

23
00:02:58,485 --> 00:03:01,363
I want to tell you something, darling.

24
00:03:01,864 --> 00:03:04,074
My first impression of you

25
00:03:05,826 --> 00:03:09,788
is a woman
who is constantly blaming herself.

26
00:03:09,788 --> 00:03:10,956
Am I right?

27
00:03:12,708 --> 00:03:15,669
You're being too hard on yourself,
my darling.

28
00:03:17,087 --> 00:03:18,922
Thank you.

29
00:03:21,508 --> 00:03:24,303
Well, you're very perceptive.

30
00:03:25,470 --> 00:03:29,683
When my husband walked out on me,
I tried ending my life.

31
00:03:29,808 --> 00:03:32,186
Well, I imagine Gabriella told you
that little tale.

32
00:03:32,811 --> 00:03:34,646
She's such a gossip.

33
00:03:35,147 --> 00:03:37,399
I now realize that was foolish.

34
00:03:37,774 --> 00:03:39,902
I have everything to live for. I do, don't I?

35
00:03:39,985 --> 00:03:42,654
I mean, is that what you see?

36
00:03:42,779 --> 00:03:44,781
I mean, do you see...

37
00:03:44,781 --> 00:03:46,825
Is my future hopeful?

38
00:03:46,950 --> 00:03:48,202
Shall I tell you something?

39
00:03:48,827 --> 00:03:52,748
I wish you were sitting here with me
because all I am seeing

40
00:03:52,789 --> 00:03:57,920
is huge, cosmic waves
moving towards you, of positive energy.

41
00:03:58,003 --> 00:04:01,757
You're bathed in a rose light, my darling.

42
00:04:02,257 --> 00:04:05,719
You've got nothing but good coming to you,
I promise you.

43
00:04:07,054 --> 00:04:11,850
Well, 40 years of marriage is a long time.
One becomes terribly dependent.

44
00:04:12,017 --> 00:04:15,312
My husband walked out on me
for one simple reason,

45
00:04:15,354 --> 00:04:17,356
I was too honest with him.

46
00:04:17,356 --> 00:04:20,150
I refused to allow him to delude himself.

47
00:04:21,235 --> 00:04:24,488
Meet Helena's ex-husband, Alfie Shepridge.

48
00:04:24,571 --> 00:04:29,451
He woke in the middle of the night,
pictured eternity, lay there in a cold sweat,

49
00:04:29,618 --> 00:04:32,579
and has not been able
to get back to sleep since.

50
00:04:32,621 --> 00:04:35,499
Suddenly, it became
all jogging and health foods.

51
00:04:35,582 --> 00:04:37,793
And give me one more set of 1 2.

52
00:04:39,336 --> 00:04:41,672
-I can't, I've had enough.
-One, two...

53
00:04:41,713 --> 00:04:43,507
-Alfie, you're doing too much.
-...three, four...

54
00:04:43,549 --> 00:04:44,716
-You'll kill your back again.
-...five...

55
00:04:44,716 --> 00:04:46,510
-He thinks he's 21 !
-...six.

56
00:04:46,552 --> 00:04:48,512
Those days are over.
You're not a young man anymore.

57
00:04:48,554 --> 00:04:49,513
Jesus.

58
00:04:49,513 --> 00:04:51,056
You do push-ups,

59
00:04:51,098 --> 00:04:53,100
but the clock still ticks. You can't fight time.

60
00:04:53,183 --> 00:04:55,394
You see?
She already has me dead and buried.

61
00:04:55,519 --> 00:04:57,646
But there's longevity in my genes,
and that's what counts.

62
00:04:57,813 --> 00:04:59,106
Genes, right?

63
00:04:59,815 --> 00:05:01,567
Poor Helena.

64
00:05:01,567 --> 00:05:04,152
She didn't understand
that truth is not beauty,

65
00:05:04,236 --> 00:05:06,989
as the poet said, but quite the opposite.

66
00:05:07,114 --> 00:05:08,031
Alfie dumped her.

67
00:05:08,490 --> 00:05:11,785
He bought a sports car.
He took a flashy bachelor pad.

68
00:05:11,827 --> 00:05:14,621
Had his teeth whitened
and his skin darkened.

69
00:05:19,293 --> 00:05:21,753
And Helena? She took it like a trouper.

70
00:05:21,753 --> 00:05:25,340
She had a nervous breakdown
and popped 40 sleeping pills.

71
00:05:25,465 --> 00:05:29,511
She has become the official burden
of her only child, Sally.

72
00:05:29,553 --> 00:05:32,181
Sally, who married Roy.

73
00:05:32,514 --> 00:05:34,516
My daughter married badly.

74
00:05:34,516 --> 00:05:36,977
Waste of education.

75
00:05:37,186 --> 00:05:39,980
He graduated from medical school
to give it all up to become a writer.

76
00:05:40,105 --> 00:05:44,985
He's had one successful novel
and since then, he's failed over and over!

77
00:05:45,027 --> 00:05:48,572
He's a one-book phenomenon.
He can't accept that! Am I right?

78
00:05:48,614 --> 00:05:52,242
I mean, do you see a future for him,
or was he just lucky the first time around?

79
00:05:52,409 --> 00:05:55,329
I want you to bring me something of his,
something that he's had close to him,

80
00:05:55,412 --> 00:05:59,917
like a scarf or a glove
or a T-shirt, all right, darling?

81
00:06:00,209 --> 00:06:01,752
I pay their bills!

82
00:06:01,877 --> 00:06:03,962
Sally can't survive on what she earns.

83
00:06:04,129 --> 00:06:06,298
He doesn't work
so he can stay at home and write.

84
00:06:06,507 --> 00:06:09,092
He's been working on
the same bloody novel for years.

85
00:06:09,510 --> 00:06:12,596
It's not entirely true,
what Helena tells her swami.

86
00:06:12,679 --> 00:06:15,098
Roy tried a while ago to earn money.

87
00:06:15,182 --> 00:06:17,184
It's not that he didn't try.

88
00:06:17,309 --> 00:06:19,811
He just wasn't much of a chauffeur.

89
00:06:22,481 --> 00:06:24,274
I've had it with that goddamned job.

90
00:06:24,274 --> 00:06:26,235
-What?
-That's it, I quit!

91
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:28,987
Please, Roy, not this conversation again!

92
00:06:29,112 --> 00:06:31,281
What are you doing home, anyway?

93
00:06:31,406 --> 00:06:32,824
What happened?

94
00:06:32,908 --> 00:06:34,868
I had an accident today.
I smashed up the car.

95
00:06:34,910 --> 00:06:35,953
What?

96
00:06:36,078 --> 00:06:39,414
I can't write all night
and then drive in the daytime!

97
00:06:39,540 --> 00:06:41,291
-I fell asleep at the wheel.
-Oh, God.

98
00:06:41,375 --> 00:06:43,710
Well, are you okay? Did anyone get hurt?

99
00:06:43,752 --> 00:06:46,672
Look, I need time to work on my book.

100
00:06:47,631 --> 00:06:50,592
When are you gonna
finish that book, anyway?

101
00:06:50,717 --> 00:06:55,597
I mean, how many times can you write
and tear up and rewrite these chapters?

102
00:06:55,764 --> 00:06:58,183
-It's like you're scared to finish.
-Okay, you know what? You're right.

103
00:06:58,225 --> 00:06:59,518
I'm gun-shy.

104
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:01,478
I can't handle it if it's confirmed, yet again,

105
00:07:01,478 --> 00:07:03,647
that all those nice things predicted about me
were wrong.

106
00:07:03,772 --> 00:07:05,315
That I was a flash in the pan.

107
00:07:05,357 --> 00:07:07,734
-Stalling is not the answer.
-Yeah.

108
00:07:07,776 --> 00:07:09,778
Jesus Christ.

109
00:07:09,820 --> 00:07:12,030
You know, all my friends have families.

110
00:07:12,155 --> 00:07:14,199
And what are we doing here?

111
00:07:15,117 --> 00:07:18,412
One way or the other,
I want to move on with our lives.

112
00:07:34,970 --> 00:07:38,015
Roy's attention was caught
by a lovely apparition

113
00:07:38,015 --> 00:07:40,767
moving into the flat across the way.

114
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:43,478
He and Sally fought so much now,

115
00:07:43,562 --> 00:07:47,816
it was hard to imagine that
they fell so much in love when they first met.

116
00:07:48,108 --> 00:07:49,234
-Are you okay?
-Yeah, I'm fine,

117
00:07:49,318 --> 00:07:50,986
but he came straight out in front of me.

118
00:07:51,028 --> 00:07:53,238
-It looks so painful.
-It's killing me.

119
00:07:53,280 --> 00:07:55,407
-It's swollen all there.
-Yeah.

120
00:07:55,699 --> 00:07:58,327
If you can move it, it's not broken.

121
00:08:00,621 --> 00:08:03,916
My guess is that you strained the metatarsal.

122
00:08:04,750 --> 00:08:07,628
-Are you a doctor?
-Unlicensed.

123
00:08:08,253 --> 00:08:09,379
May I?

124
00:08:15,385 --> 00:08:18,597
-Her foot's okay?
-Oh, yeah, it's better than okay.

125
00:08:21,099 --> 00:08:22,976
It's very pretty.

126
00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,898
"So much depends

127
00:08:27,981 --> 00:08:29,983
"upon a red wheelbarrow

128
00:08:32,402 --> 00:08:35,447
"glazed with rain water

129
00:08:35,614 --> 00:08:37,908
"beside the white chickens."

130
00:08:40,661 --> 00:08:42,287
And Sally's ass.

131
00:08:46,124 --> 00:08:48,210
I'm paraphrasing, of course.

132
00:08:52,464 --> 00:08:56,051
You know, the day I graduated
from medical school was the day

133
00:08:56,176 --> 00:09:00,097
that I knew that
I would never practice medicine.

134
00:09:00,764 --> 00:09:02,182
There was no question in my mind

135
00:09:02,266 --> 00:09:04,434
that I was gonna write,
and that I was gonna make it as a writer.

136
00:09:04,560 --> 00:09:06,562
I mean, you know how you feel those things?

137
00:09:06,603 --> 00:09:08,647
And Roy's first book did make it.

138
00:09:08,689 --> 00:09:10,983
At least it showed real promise.

139
00:09:11,149 --> 00:09:11,984
But that was then.

140
00:09:12,901 --> 00:09:15,988
And as the years passed,
Sally put her dreams on hold

141
00:09:16,071 --> 00:09:17,322
and went to work.

142
00:09:17,406 --> 00:09:20,909
Now, the hours are 24/7.

143
00:09:22,286 --> 00:09:25,289
The work involves everything from,
I don't know,

144
00:09:25,289 --> 00:09:29,126
filing papers to keeping clients happy
and painters pampered,

145
00:09:29,334 --> 00:09:31,753
to getting my lunches.

146
00:09:31,795 --> 00:09:34,256
So, what are your ambitions?

147
00:09:34,798 --> 00:09:39,887
Well, I've got a degree in art
and a background in art history,

148
00:09:40,304 --> 00:09:43,682
and I've worked for the museum
and some photographers.

149
00:09:44,057 --> 00:09:45,851
How did you hear about this job?

150
00:09:45,851 --> 00:09:47,853
My friend, Jane Brooks,
who works at The Geller Gallery,

151
00:09:47,978 --> 00:09:49,396
she told me you were looking for someone.

152
00:09:49,438 --> 00:09:52,441
And when she said
it was The Clemente Gallery...

153
00:09:57,070 --> 00:09:59,531
Well, you're going to school with the best.

154
00:09:59,615 --> 00:10:03,076
I've been working at The Geller Gallery
for four years now,

155
00:10:03,285 --> 00:10:08,874
and I've really had an education,
even though I can't stand Lois Geller.

156
00:10:08,999 --> 00:10:11,502
Well, Greg's a dynamo.

157
00:10:11,543 --> 00:10:14,588
And I must say, extremely attractive.

158
00:10:14,713 --> 00:10:17,841
Sally, don't get a crush on your boss.

159
00:10:17,966 --> 00:10:20,302
That way lies total madness.

160
00:10:22,054 --> 00:10:26,725
Roy was asked by Henry Strangler
to read his first novel and give an opinion.

161
00:10:26,767 --> 00:10:30,103
And Strangler's first novel seemed
so much better than Roy's fourth,

162
00:10:30,187 --> 00:10:31,813
he grew discouraged.

163
00:10:32,814 --> 00:10:36,485
All that cheered him up was
the beautiful creature in red across the way,

164
00:10:36,485 --> 00:10:40,280
whose life grew increasingly tantalizing
behind her windowpane.

165
00:11:07,891 --> 00:11:10,978
-I'm sorry. Am I disturbing you?
-No, not at all.

166
00:11:11,228 --> 00:11:13,021
I love the guitar.

167
00:11:13,397 --> 00:11:16,942
-Recently moved in?
-Just for the summer.

168
00:11:16,984 --> 00:11:19,486
-Should I close this window?
-No, I'm not working.

169
00:11:19,611 --> 00:11:22,114
I'm just reading a friend's new book.

170
00:11:25,117 --> 00:11:27,494
It reads beautiful to Boccherini.

171
00:11:27,494 --> 00:11:29,663
Do you know his music?

172
00:11:30,247 --> 00:11:32,082
Quite impressed.

173
00:11:32,583 --> 00:11:36,712
Well, anyway, if it gets too annoying,
just let me know and I'll stop, okay?

174
00:11:40,382 --> 00:11:42,009
-Anyone want a top-up?
-I would.

175
00:11:53,020 --> 00:11:54,646
Hey.

176
00:11:54,688 --> 00:11:56,815
-I read your new book.
-What?

177
00:11:57,316 --> 00:11:59,735
-I was overwhelmed.
-No.

178
00:11:59,818 --> 00:12:02,905
-No, you're kidding.
-Yes. My confidence is gone now.

179
00:12:02,905 --> 00:12:06,033
-What? Don't be ridiculous.
-Yeah.

180
00:12:06,116 --> 00:12:07,618
I'm speechless.

181
00:12:08,744 --> 00:12:10,412
You liked it?

182
00:12:10,496 --> 00:12:11,747
Damn!

183
00:12:11,747 --> 00:12:14,208
Obviously, you know,
I haven't shown it to anybody before.

184
00:12:14,208 --> 00:12:16,210
But I need to tweak a few things,
still, of course...

185
00:12:16,210 --> 00:12:19,796
Of course it didn't hurt that I read it
to some very beautiful Boccherini,

186
00:12:19,796 --> 00:12:23,050
played on the guitar by that knockout,
whose name I still don't know.

187
00:12:23,050 --> 00:12:26,178
-The woman in the window?
-Yes, the woman in the window.

188
00:12:26,220 --> 00:12:29,097
Well, no wonder you're having trouble
finishing your bloody book.

189
00:12:30,641 --> 00:12:32,226
-I finished it.
-No.

190
00:12:32,309 --> 00:12:33,519
-I handed it in yesterday.
-Well done.

191
00:12:33,602 --> 00:12:35,103
No, I'm a nervous wreck.

192
00:12:35,187 --> 00:12:37,064
I don't know what I'll do if it doesn't make it.

193
00:12:37,147 --> 00:12:39,066
-Come on.
-No, I don't know what I'll do.

194
00:12:39,191 --> 00:12:41,485
I'll be chauffeuring
the goddamned limos again...

195
00:12:41,485 --> 00:12:42,945
-Rubbish!
-All my confidence is gone.

196
00:12:43,070 --> 00:12:46,114
Because of you, partially,
my confidence is gone.

197
00:13:07,803 --> 00:13:09,221
Hello?

198
00:13:09,304 --> 00:13:11,223
Hi, Mum. Come in.

199
00:13:11,306 --> 00:13:13,433
Why does she have to
come over here so often?

200
00:13:13,600 --> 00:13:16,103
I mean, it's once, twice. It's endless!

201
00:13:16,186 --> 00:13:19,314
I'm trying to relax here.
My nerves are shot from waiting.

202
00:13:19,398 --> 00:13:21,775
I know. She can't stand to be alone.

203
00:13:21,900 --> 00:13:24,528
And, you know, I worry about her, Roy.

204
00:13:25,153 --> 00:13:27,531
She's taken to talking to herself a bit, lately.

205
00:13:27,698 --> 00:13:29,533
And you encourage her
with that phony mind-reader.

206
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:30,909
Well, okay, yes!

207
00:13:31,076 --> 00:13:33,912
Cristal is a fake. We know that, but...

208
00:13:34,163 --> 00:13:37,374
Thank God she buys into it,
and it gives her peace of mind,

209
00:13:37,416 --> 00:13:39,710
and don't you try and spoil it for her, please.

210
00:13:39,751 --> 00:13:41,044
Okay, look, I'm not gonna say anything.

211
00:13:41,086 --> 00:13:44,965
I just don't think you help her by going
into that garbage about foretelling her future.

212
00:13:45,007 --> 00:13:46,550
She needs medicine, not illusions.

213
00:13:46,550 --> 00:13:49,761
No, not if the illusions
work better than the medicine.

214
00:13:52,014 --> 00:13:54,266
-Here I am, darling.
-Hi, Mum!

215
00:13:54,683 --> 00:13:58,687
I've just come from a session with Cristal.
That woman is uncanny.

216
00:13:59,313 --> 00:14:02,357
I know you have
a cold, scientific background, Roy.

217
00:14:02,524 --> 00:14:05,652
-Yes, I have a tough time with mumbo-jumbo.
-Roy, please!

218
00:14:05,652 --> 00:14:07,279
Look, if you feel better, then it's just...
I don't know.

219
00:14:07,321 --> 00:14:08,989
We discussed you.

220
00:14:09,114 --> 00:14:10,657
She was very positive about your future.

221
00:14:10,741 --> 00:14:13,410
Though, to be perfectly candid,
she didn't see it in literature.

222
00:14:13,410 --> 00:14:14,453
Well, that's too bad.

223
00:14:14,536 --> 00:14:16,288
Let's hope she's channeling
the wrong spirits.

224
00:14:16,413 --> 00:14:17,414
She's rarely wrong.

225
00:14:17,414 --> 00:14:19,708
Mum, Roy just handed in
his new novel this week.

226
00:14:19,917 --> 00:14:22,169
He's on tenterhooks while they read it.

227
00:14:22,211 --> 00:14:24,421
Well, I'm only saying
not to build your hopes up.

228
00:14:24,421 --> 00:14:26,715
-Cristal said...
-No, I don't care what Cristal said. Okay?

229
00:14:26,757 --> 00:14:29,426
Mum, nobody's infallible! Please! Let it...

230
00:14:29,551 --> 00:14:32,513
I know she's always right with your future,
but it doesn't mean she knows Roy's.

231
00:14:32,638 --> 00:14:34,431
She's never even met him!

232
00:14:34,431 --> 00:14:37,309
She was very complimentary
in her readings about Roy,

233
00:14:37,476 --> 00:14:40,604
just not necessarily as a writer.
Not at this point in time.

234
00:14:40,729 --> 00:14:43,899
She did say one day,
perhaps, with maturity...

235
00:14:44,024 --> 00:14:47,152
Oh, by the way,
could I have another glove of yours?

236
00:14:47,319 --> 00:14:49,696
I'm sorry, but she lost the first one.

237
00:14:49,863 --> 00:14:51,114
What glove?

238
00:14:52,115 --> 00:14:54,618
Did you give her my missing glove? Jesus!

239
00:14:58,497 --> 00:15:00,874
Did he take the book home with him?

240
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:06,171
But no clue whether he could
get to it this weekend?

241
00:15:07,047 --> 00:15:08,966
Okay. No, I'll call back.

242
00:15:37,494 --> 00:15:41,415
Okay, now let's go back
and take a look at Alfie Shepridge.

243
00:15:41,582 --> 00:15:42,624
Since his divorce,

244
00:15:42,749 --> 00:15:45,419
Alfie Shepridge did not exactly find himself

245
00:15:45,586 --> 00:15:49,047
leading the thirtysomething life
he envisioned in his new digs.

246
00:15:56,847 --> 00:16:01,143
Friends fixed him up with one or two women
they thought might be appropriate.

247
00:16:01,185 --> 00:16:02,769
Always that word...

248
00:16:02,936 --> 00:16:04,271
But it was not what he had in mind.

249
00:16:04,730 --> 00:16:08,275
I'm sorry about the stick,
but I've just had my hip replaced.

250
00:16:08,609 --> 00:16:11,486
At first, I thought I fell down and broke it.

251
00:16:11,528 --> 00:16:13,197
But what actually happened was,

252
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:15,782
it broke, and then I fell down.

253
00:16:15,991 --> 00:16:17,951
Do you see the difference?

254
00:16:18,619 --> 00:16:21,371
He tried spending time
with younger colleagues from his firm,

255
00:16:21,371 --> 00:16:24,458
but he felt even more out of place
and ridiculous.

256
00:16:28,170 --> 00:16:32,799
And then, one day, after months
of loneliness and awkward experiences,

257
00:16:32,841 --> 00:16:36,220
he took his daughter for a walk
and made a startling announcement.

258
00:16:36,261 --> 00:16:39,473
I've met a woman, I'm very much in love,
I'm going to get married.

259
00:16:39,473 --> 00:16:41,975
-Isn't that fabulous?
-You're kidding.

260
00:16:42,059 --> 00:16:43,852
No. You seem shocked.

261
00:16:44,728 --> 00:16:47,064
Is that what this walk's about?

262
00:16:47,231 --> 00:16:48,857
So private and mysterious.

263
00:16:48,941 --> 00:16:51,401
Well, I told your mother
and, you know, she was surprised,

264
00:16:51,485 --> 00:16:53,320
but she took it well.

265
00:16:53,487 --> 00:16:57,616
Apparently, this woman she's been seeing,
who gives her guidance about her future,

266
00:16:57,783 --> 00:16:59,952
has given her a lot of strength emotionally.

267
00:17:00,035 --> 00:17:03,413
Anyway, I would like you to
help choose some perfume with me.

268
00:17:03,455 --> 00:17:04,748
Would you do that?

269
00:17:04,998 --> 00:17:07,793
So, who is this woman
you're going to marry?

270
00:17:09,002 --> 00:17:11,380
Her name is Charmaine.

271
00:17:11,630 --> 00:17:14,049
She's an actress! Half his age!

272
00:17:14,049 --> 00:17:16,051
This is all for the good.

273
00:17:16,051 --> 00:17:20,973
I've got a strong feeling that
this is a positive turning point in your life.

274
00:17:21,056 --> 00:17:25,477
But where is my life heading?
I need direction.

275
00:17:26,854 --> 00:17:31,316
-Is my future as empty as I feel it is?
-Listen. This is a pivotal moment.

276
00:17:31,483 --> 00:17:34,236
Now, you've got several paths
to choose from.

277
00:17:34,361 --> 00:17:36,363
You've got to make sure
you choose the right one.

278
00:17:36,488 --> 00:17:39,783
My darling! I'm seeing you triumphing.

279
00:17:41,034 --> 00:17:43,036
I'm seeing you with a new love.

280
00:17:43,036 --> 00:17:46,957
-What, a new love for me?
-I can see it! I can see it!

281
00:17:47,040 --> 00:17:51,420
This development in your husband's life
can only be favorable to you.

282
00:17:51,420 --> 00:17:53,839
You're saying I shall meet a new love?

283
00:17:53,839 --> 00:17:55,716
And I'll tell you something else.

284
00:17:55,883 --> 00:17:59,887
Your husband will never love
this woman he's marrying

285
00:18:00,012 --> 00:18:01,889
as much as he loved you.

286
00:18:01,972 --> 00:18:05,684
I've kept all his letters. They were so adoring.

287
00:18:05,684 --> 00:18:09,188
Christ, no one wants to get old!
I don't want to get old!

288
00:18:09,730 --> 00:18:11,648
And you're saying I won't be alone?

289
00:18:11,732 --> 00:18:14,568
I don't want to spend
the rest of my life alone.

290
00:18:14,610 --> 00:18:16,195
Oh, my sweetheart.

291
00:18:16,320 --> 00:18:19,948
You are entering a period of great fulfillment.

292
00:18:21,950 --> 00:18:25,829
I'm seeing a handsome stranger
coming into your life.

293
00:18:27,623 --> 00:18:29,583
Powerful attraction.

294
00:18:29,791 --> 00:18:32,085
You're like two magnets.

295
00:18:38,091 --> 00:18:43,680
Sally, can you call Lucien Moss
and get me out of my lunch tomorrow?

296
00:18:43,847 --> 00:18:45,474
-Reschedule?
-Well, yes.

297
00:18:45,641 --> 00:18:47,893
-Tell him I'll call to reschedule, yeah.
-Okay.

298
00:18:48,018 --> 00:18:52,397
And arrange a flight to Venice
for my wife and myself for the 25th.

299
00:18:52,481 --> 00:18:56,109
Which reminds me,
I need you to come with me this afternoon.

300
00:19:05,327 --> 00:19:08,080
Yes, they're lovely.
I particularly like that one.

301
00:19:08,163 --> 00:19:11,792
Sally, could you please come?
Take a look at this.

302
00:19:11,792 --> 00:19:14,545
-Which ones are you thinking of?
-These diamonds.

303
00:19:15,796 --> 00:19:17,798
Or the pearls.

304
00:19:18,674 --> 00:19:21,969
-Well, they're both beautiful.
-They are.

305
00:19:22,052 --> 00:19:25,681
Now, what's the best price
you'll give me on these?

306
00:19:25,848 --> 00:19:29,893
Well, these are Victorian diamonds.
Brilliant cut.

307
00:19:30,352 --> 00:19:32,855
These are $50,000.

308
00:19:32,938 --> 00:19:35,899
These are what we call natural pearls.

309
00:19:35,983 --> 00:19:38,694
These are slightly later,
Edwardian, turn-of-the-century,

310
00:19:38,777 --> 00:19:40,320
and these are $1 5,000.

311
00:19:42,447 --> 00:19:44,825
Which would my wife prefer?

312
00:19:45,576 --> 00:19:47,286
What's she like?

313
00:19:48,370 --> 00:19:50,998
-Remote.
-Remote?

314
00:19:52,374 --> 00:19:56,920
She loves diamonds, but, you know,
these pearls are so sexy.

315
00:19:57,671 --> 00:19:59,673
And so much less expensive.

316
00:20:01,049 --> 00:20:04,261
-Would you like to try them on?
-They're not for me.

317
00:20:04,303 --> 00:20:09,099
I understand, but perhaps it might help,
if the gentleman could see how they looked.

318
00:20:09,183 --> 00:20:11,476
-Shall I?
-If you don't mind.

319
00:20:11,602 --> 00:20:13,103
All right.

320
00:20:14,188 --> 00:20:16,565
-Let's see.
-Let's see.

321
00:20:22,487 --> 00:20:24,156
-Very nice.
-Yeah.

322
00:20:25,782 --> 00:20:27,451
Yep, yep, yep.

323
00:20:28,619 --> 00:20:30,204
Wow. Wow!

324
00:20:30,621 --> 00:20:32,164
Let me see.

325
00:20:33,415 --> 00:20:36,543
-They really frame your face beautifully.
-They do, sir.

326
00:20:36,668 --> 00:20:40,005
Well, I do have a good shape
for long earrings.

327
00:20:40,130 --> 00:20:41,507
You do.

328
00:20:41,882 --> 00:20:45,886
Well, you love these more than the pearls,
don't you?

329
00:20:46,053 --> 00:20:48,347
-I do. I'm afraid so.
-Okay, God.

330
00:20:48,472 --> 00:20:52,351
I hope, for this kind of money,
she looks as good in them as you do.

331
00:20:52,351 --> 00:20:53,352
Yep.

332
00:20:55,395 --> 00:20:58,982
-Do I have to take them off?
-That's life, I'm afraid.

333
00:20:59,107 --> 00:21:00,859
-Sorry.
-Oh, well.

334
00:21:01,860 --> 00:21:04,029
They were good for a minute.

335
00:21:04,279 --> 00:21:07,616
Oh, I'm dying to see just what
my father thinks is so perfect for him.

336
00:21:07,699 --> 00:21:10,786
-Can you tell I'm a little skeptical?
-Yeah. Why?

337
00:21:10,828 --> 00:21:13,413
I mean, who is she?
How long has he known her to marry her?

338
00:21:13,580 --> 00:21:17,000
And why is some young actress
rushing off to marry him?

339
00:21:18,418 --> 00:21:20,587
An actress. Actress in what?

340
00:21:20,671 --> 00:21:23,715
-What's her name?
-Charmaine.

341
00:21:23,715 --> 00:21:25,717
I keep wanting to say "chow mein."

342
00:21:25,843 --> 00:21:27,886
Why do you keep looking out the window?

343
00:21:28,011 --> 00:21:29,346
I don't.

344
00:21:29,388 --> 00:21:32,057
You're so nervous. You seem edgy.
What's up?

345
00:21:32,140 --> 00:21:34,643
Well, if I can hear something
about my book...

346
00:21:35,602 --> 00:21:38,772
-Oh, Christ, who's that?
-One guess!

347
00:21:49,825 --> 00:21:51,451
You look very lovely, darling.

348
00:21:51,618 --> 00:21:54,204
Forgive me for barging in.
I've just come from Cristal's.

349
00:21:54,204 --> 00:21:57,749
She had some things to say
about your father's upcoming wedding.

350
00:21:57,875 --> 00:22:01,712
-Is there something I could sip on?
-Helena, you've sipped us dry.

351
00:22:01,753 --> 00:22:05,716
Unless you're willing to try cooking sherry.
I'm just joking.

352
00:22:05,883 --> 00:22:09,011
By the way, she said you would hear
about your book any day now,

353
00:22:09,011 --> 00:22:11,805
but not to be upset
if the verdict was negative.

354
00:22:11,889 --> 00:22:15,809
I hope Cristal put your mind at ease
about Dad's remarrying.

355
00:22:15,809 --> 00:22:16,852
Cristal said...

356
00:22:17,019 --> 00:22:21,148
She said he would never be as enchanted
with this other woman as he was with me.

357
00:22:21,231 --> 00:22:23,609
Well, I'm sure she's right.

358
00:22:23,609 --> 00:22:27,821
-Have you met her?
-Actually, we're going to meet her tonight.

359
00:22:27,946 --> 00:22:31,283
Dad's taking us to the park
for drinks and a concert.

360
00:22:32,993 --> 00:22:37,289
Cristal and I were talking about
a new love that I will soon be meeting.

361
00:22:37,414 --> 00:22:39,917
Wow. That's exciting news. Isn't it, Roy?

362
00:22:40,083 --> 00:22:43,462
Yeah, you will meet a tall, dark stranger.

363
00:22:43,462 --> 00:22:46,673
I will not be alone. I will find love.
I can rest assured.

364
00:22:46,715 --> 00:22:49,718
What does she charge you
for this message of hope?

365
00:22:49,885 --> 00:22:53,055
It's not hope, it's a certainty.
Cristal predicts it.

366
00:22:53,180 --> 00:22:56,183
-He doesn't believe, Sally.
-No, I believe, unfortunately,

367
00:22:56,183 --> 00:23:00,270
that you will meet the same tall, dark stranger
that we all eventually meet.

368
00:23:00,270 --> 00:23:02,981
And look where that cynicism has got you
over the years.

369
00:23:02,981 --> 00:23:04,816
Cristal knows things
she couldn't possibly know

370
00:23:04,942 --> 00:23:05,817
if she wasn't blessed with a gift.

371
00:23:05,984 --> 00:23:07,361
Look, did it ever occur to you

372
00:23:07,402 --> 00:23:09,821
that she might be getting her information
from your masseuse?

373
00:23:10,030 --> 00:23:12,032
I mean, not to mention
what you give away without realizing it...

374
00:23:12,115 --> 00:23:13,367
-Roy!
-What?

375
00:23:13,408 --> 00:23:16,203
She tells her what she wants to hear
and takes her money.

376
00:23:16,203 --> 00:23:17,746
Well, you take my money

377
00:23:17,913 --> 00:23:19,456
and certainly don't tell me
what I want to hear.

378
00:23:19,581 --> 00:23:22,668
Why can you two not be together
without tension?

379
00:23:22,751 --> 00:23:25,254
I'm just trying to prepare
your husband for a blow

380
00:23:25,420 --> 00:23:26,713
should his work be rejected.

381
00:23:26,839 --> 00:23:29,007
Well, my work will not be rejected.

382
00:23:29,091 --> 00:23:33,220
And if it is, this hustler you see
made a 50-50 guess.

383
00:23:33,262 --> 00:23:35,097
You see how that works?

384
00:23:35,180 --> 00:23:36,682
Mum?

385
00:23:36,765 --> 00:23:40,185
Please, just give him a break.
He's vulnerable right now.

386
00:23:40,227 --> 00:23:43,230
Hasn't a spiritual bone in his body.
How can he write books?

387
00:23:43,272 --> 00:23:46,316
So, Cristal said you're gonna meet someone.

388
00:23:46,316 --> 00:23:48,777
Isn't that good news?

389
00:23:48,819 --> 00:23:52,155
She also said that
you're perfectly able to conceive.

390
00:23:52,197 --> 00:23:54,908
Well, of course I am, and you know that, too.

391
00:23:54,992 --> 00:23:58,620
Well, I couldn't after your brother died.

392
00:23:58,745 --> 00:24:01,707
I mean, the doctor said
it was psychological, but...

393
00:24:01,707 --> 00:24:04,418
I couldn't give Alfie another child,
and he longed for a son.

394
00:24:04,543 --> 00:24:07,337
Please, let's not relive everything constantly.

395
00:24:07,337 --> 00:24:09,339
Anyway, look, we must go.

396
00:24:31,820 --> 00:24:33,405
There they are.

397
00:24:33,822 --> 00:24:35,073
Hello.

398
00:24:35,073 --> 00:24:37,117
-This is Sally and this is Roy.
-Hello. All right?

399
00:24:37,201 --> 00:24:38,869
-Hey, how are you?
-Charmaine Foxx.

400
00:24:38,952 --> 00:24:39,870
-From America.
-Yeah.

401
00:24:40,078 --> 00:24:41,872
You didn't tell me. Never tells me nothing.

402
00:24:42,080 --> 00:24:43,123
Hello.

403
00:24:44,458 --> 00:24:47,669
Don't want to flash everyone now. No.

404
00:24:49,004 --> 00:24:50,589
-Well.
-So...

405
00:25:01,975 --> 00:25:04,019
Dad said you were an actress.

406
00:25:04,353 --> 00:25:05,979
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

407
00:25:05,979 --> 00:25:10,901
I tried it in Hollywood for a while,
but if you don't know people, it...

408
00:25:11,985 --> 00:25:14,196
It's like a vicious circle, you know?

409
00:25:14,988 --> 00:25:16,114
Yeah.

410
00:25:17,199 --> 00:25:19,284
So, what are your plans?

411
00:25:19,409 --> 00:25:20,494
I think...

412
00:25:20,536 --> 00:25:23,872
Well, her plans are, you know,
to be my wife, Mrs. Alfie Shepridge.

413
00:25:24,039 --> 00:25:26,333
She's going to be the mother of my son.
The boy...

414
00:25:26,416 --> 00:25:29,753
One day I'll teach him football,
or something like that. Isn't that right?

415
00:25:31,922 --> 00:25:33,382
Anyway, she... You were in...

416
00:25:33,423 --> 00:25:36,969
-She was in a few movies, films, on TV.
-Stop it.

417
00:25:37,052 --> 00:25:39,179
-But you were.
-Just small parts.

418
00:25:39,388 --> 00:25:41,765
-What were the films?
-Science fiction.

419
00:25:43,642 --> 00:25:47,020
I was the leader's daughter,
but from another galaxy.

420
00:25:47,187 --> 00:25:49,982
That's right up your street, Roy.
Roy is a doctor.

421
00:25:50,148 --> 00:25:53,527
Well, actually, he wrote a novel
about a physicist,

422
00:25:53,610 --> 00:25:55,988
-based on Werner Heisenberg, isn't it?
-Yeah.

423
00:25:56,655 --> 00:25:57,614
Who?

424
00:25:58,282 --> 00:26:01,451
So, how long have you known each other?

425
00:26:01,451 --> 00:26:02,661
-Three months. No...
-No.

426
00:26:02,786 --> 00:26:05,038
-Two months.
-Two months. Yeah.

427
00:26:06,456 --> 00:26:09,084
So, you've actually just met.

428
00:26:09,918 --> 00:26:11,920
Well, we've spent every day together
since we did meet.

429
00:26:11,920 --> 00:26:13,338
-And can you blame me?
-We have. Yeah.

430
00:26:13,505 --> 00:26:17,634
I mean, I was besotted with
charming Charmaine from the very first day

431
00:26:17,801 --> 00:26:20,387
and it just, you know...

432
00:26:20,387 --> 00:26:21,388
So that's...

433
00:26:21,471 --> 00:26:22,681
So, how did you meet?

434
00:26:23,348 --> 00:26:26,018
A mutual acquaintance introduced us.
That's how we met.

435
00:26:26,018 --> 00:26:27,186
Yeah.

436
00:26:27,644 --> 00:26:29,980
Here, Alfie was not being truthful.

437
00:26:29,980 --> 00:26:33,192
Technically, maybe,
but that wasn't the whole story.

438
00:26:35,152 --> 00:26:36,612
-Hello.
-Come in.

439
00:26:39,281 --> 00:26:41,950
So, you're Charmiane.

440
00:26:41,950 --> 00:26:44,119
-Charmaine.
-Charmiane.

441
00:26:44,119 --> 00:26:47,998
Sorry. Come in.
Yeah, he said you were very pretty.

442
00:26:49,875 --> 00:26:52,127
-My body's how I make my living, isn't it?
-Yes.

443
00:26:52,252 --> 00:26:54,838
-I'm always working out.
-Good. Well, me, too.

444
00:26:54,963 --> 00:26:56,798
Look, feel this.

445
00:26:59,593 --> 00:27:01,845
-Not bad.
-You're buff, ain't you?

446
00:27:02,554 --> 00:27:03,639
Yeah.

447
00:27:03,764 --> 00:27:06,183
-Would you like a drink?
-Yeah. All right.

448
00:27:06,225 --> 00:27:07,851
Good. Okay.

449
00:27:09,228 --> 00:27:11,980
Geoffrey Sweeney gave me your number.

450
00:27:12,147 --> 00:27:13,815
-Geoffrey?
-Yeah.

451
00:27:13,815 --> 00:27:15,943
-Geoffrey...
-Yes.

452
00:27:15,984 --> 00:27:19,988
-God, I know millions of Geoffreys.
-Oh, yeah? Well, doesn't matter.

453
00:27:20,948 --> 00:27:22,783
You have to forgive me
if I seem a little awkward,

454
00:27:22,950 --> 00:27:25,911
-but I don't usually do this sort of thing.
-Right.

455
00:27:26,703 --> 00:27:30,123
I assume it's hygienic and all,
you know what I mean?

456
00:27:30,290 --> 00:27:32,125
-Hygienic?
-Yeah.

457
00:27:33,585 --> 00:27:36,380
-Are you having a laugh?
-No, I'm just checking.

458
00:27:36,421 --> 00:27:38,715
I won't give you AIDS,
if that's what you mean.

459
00:27:38,799 --> 00:27:41,593
No, I wasn't thinking about AIDS. God, no.

460
00:27:41,635 --> 00:27:43,387
There's a man in my firm who's got herpes.

461
00:27:43,470 --> 00:27:46,431
-No, relax, don't have to worry.
-All right. Yeah.

462
00:27:46,431 --> 00:27:50,644
Basically, I'm an actress.
I'm just doing this part-time.

463
00:27:50,769 --> 00:27:54,606
Good. You look pretty. Okay.

464
00:27:56,108 --> 00:27:58,902
-Shall we settle the business?
-Oh, yeah. Okay.

465
00:27:58,944 --> 00:28:01,738
-They told you it was 350, yeah?
-Yeah, okay.

466
00:28:01,780 --> 00:28:04,741
Here's 500, and you can keep the change.
All right?

467
00:28:04,950 --> 00:28:06,952
Oh, thank you.

468
00:28:06,994 --> 00:28:09,997
I mean, you know,
I wasn't thinking about AIDS.

469
00:28:15,210 --> 00:28:16,253
Oi.

470
00:28:16,378 --> 00:28:18,547
-Shall we get on with it?
-What?

471
00:28:18,630 --> 00:28:21,425
-Do you want to get on with it?
-Yeah.

472
00:28:22,176 --> 00:28:23,051
Okay.

473
00:28:29,099 --> 00:28:32,644
-Forty years is a long time to be married.
-Yeah, it's almost half a century.

474
00:28:32,686 --> 00:28:36,523
What happened is that my wife, Helena,
she allowed herself to become old,

475
00:28:36,648 --> 00:28:37,941
and I wasn't prepared
to accept that nonsense.

476
